This benchmark  is shown that:
who has better performance when DB-file is ONE-DATABASE-FILE mode or  INDEX-FILE&DATA-FILE mode under B+ Tree Structured.

Tested conclusions are:
Read and Write performance is almost no difference between them.
But it is easier to DELETE or UPDATE operate in INDEX-FILE&DATA-FILE mode.
So nessDB v1.5 is using INDEX-FILE&DATA-FILE mode.

Test Environment informations:
Keys:		20 bytes each
Values:		100 bytes each
Entries:	20000000
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
nessDB:		version 1.4(B+Tree)
LRU:		closed....
Date:		Fri Aug 26 15:19:21 2011
CPU:		2 *  Intel(R) Pentium(R) Dual  CPU  T3200  @ 2.00GHz
CPUCache:	1024 KB


1)ONE-DATABASE-FILE mode
========================

Database size:	4G(data is byte-alignment)
+-----------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------+---------------------+
|write		(succ:20000000): 0.000018 sec/op; 54314.9 writes/sec(estimated); 10.9 MB/sec; cost:368.223(sec)
+-----------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------+---------------------+
|readseq	(found:10000): 0.000008 sec/op; 125257.7 reads /sec(estimated); 25.1 MB/sec; cost:0.080(sec)
+-----------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------+---------------------+
|readrandom	(found:10000): 0.013128 sec/op; 76.2 reads /sec(estimated); 0.0 MB/sec; cost:131.276(sec)  
+-----------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------+---------------------+

Completely Cold-Start:
+-----------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------+---------------------+
|readrandom	(found:10000): 0.017638 sec/op; 56.7 reads /sec(estimated); 0.0 MB/sec; cost:176.382(sec)
+-----------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------+---------------------+


